varargs (variable-length arguments) in Java are a powerful feature that lets you pass zero or more arguments to a method without explicitly creating an array.

public class Main {
    static int sum(int... numbers) {
        int total = 0;
        for (int num : numbers) {
            total += num;
        }
        return total;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(sum());             // 0
        System.out.println(sum(1, 2, 3));      // 6
        System.out.println(sum(10, 20, 30, 40)); // 100
    }
}


🔍 Rules to Remember
You can pass any number of arguments, including none.

You can’t have more than one varargs parameter in a method.

It must be the last parameter: